TEXT(beginproblem()); # standard preamble to each problem.

Context("Numeric");
Context()->flags->set(useBaseTenLog=>1);

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;
$p = random(1,4,1);
$m = random(2,3,1);
$d = random(3,7,1);
$c = random(2,$d-1,1);
if ($c == 3 && $d == 4){$d = 5};

$a = "$m*e^$p";
$root = exp(-$c/$d);
$b = round($root*10000)/10000;
$r = round(($root-1)*10000)/10000;
$k = round(-$c/$d*10000)/10000;
$dec_r = round(($root-1)*10000)/10000;
$dec_k = round(-$c/$d*10000)/10000;


BEGIN_TEXT
Give the growth factor \(b\), the starting value \(a\), the growth rate \(r\), and the value of \(k\) when \(Q\) is written in the form \(Q = ae^{kt}\). If there is exponential is decay, then your growth rate should negative.
For help entering logarithms, see \{ AnswerFormatHelp("logarithms") \}
$BR
$BR
\( \displaystyle Q = $m e^{($p - \frac{$c t}{$d})} \) has:
$BR
$BR
\( b = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
$BR
\( a = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
$BR
\( r = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
$BR
\( k = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
END_TEXT

ANS(Real("$b")->cmp() );
ANS(Real("$a")->cmp() );
ANS(Real("$r")->cmp() );
ANS(Real("$k")->cmp() );


